<font color="#FF0000">HELLO, GOODBYE, STOPPING BYE</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jan 17 22:50:44 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
I post this openly, and God willing, honestly. I just spent most of the afternoon and early evening reading and &quot;catching up&quot; on threads.  You all have a lot to be proud of, and some old sores (in my opinion) that persist. I feel this site has continued on well, and I am glad.<br><br>
I have not posted as &quot;anon&quot; or &quot;anonomous&quot; or as &quot;-&quot; or anybody. Period. I made a deal with Arthur, Chet, and our gracious host, Marc, in early December, that I would 'withdraw with honor&quot; (excuse my pun) and I did, completely.  <br><br>
Since then I have received about 40 or 50 e mails, mostly goating me to get re-involved. I choose, not always easy, to ignore them. I knew that if I read the actual site, I would probably lose it and flame at someone or some issue.  I am glad to see Jed awaken out of his long slumber, as a east coast protestor this West Coast SDS-er is glad to see that at least one protestor is left.  I will not engage in any personal shots, although I saw plenty aimed at me.  Sorry, folks, but many trolls live in troll-land. I have kept my word, and with this post, will continue to go back and on with my life. Tanker can verify some of my recent frustrations regarding Viet Nam Sites. Ask him b/c if you want to.<br><br>
I hope the new year found you all better.  Arthurs post above this truly moved me, hence my breaking my code of removal. Art: PTSD of the Viet Nam variety, and it truly deserves a DSM IV diagnosis critieria of its own, has no limits or predictions. What my 25 years of being a shrink has told me, however, is to talk it, shout it, write it, until you are so emptied of its poison, that only goodness can refill you.<br><br>
As one of the early posters, (I think) I was privileged to share early moments with the like of Tanker, Chet, DocDel, and Sarg4444. I still continue b/c with many. That I lost one along the way to mistaken assumptions is truly a sorrow, but nothing in comparison to what you vets survived.  <br><br>
If this site taught me anything, it has nothing to do with the rightness or wrongness of the war, the correctness or incorrectness of our system, but rather, that there are some incredible noble people who just happened to get in the way of a war and survive.  It has been my priviledge to share some space with some of them.  I am grateful for those interchanges.  <br><br>
We are all so much older now, we were so much younger then. I can only hope that we grow older, and wiser, and more tolerant of each other.  Relax Ed, I am pulling back into my isolation again.  Arthur, I truly hope that you find the missing piece that I know you are seeking.  I wish I could help you or offer a map, but there just aren't any, professionally or personally.  I wish you, and all of you, the best of luck, hope, healing, and honest communication without trolls who wish (for what ever secondary gain they get from it) to disrupt the flow of ideas.  Without the free flow of ideas, we are no better than the animals of the jungle.  Fight on, men and Ladies, do not let the jungle grow over you, and us.<br><br>
Dr. Barry C. Spatz<br>
Santa Ana, CA.
